file_scan: prevent a bad close(2) on early error

Without this change, fd is initiated as 0.
If an error occurs before we open(2) the file,
the cleanup code will try to close that unrelated file descriptor.

commit.message:
dbfile: rename: remove the existing file on conflict

We have file1 with some hashes and file2 with some hashes
On the filesystem, file2 has been renamed to file1, which is
effectively removed
This change implements this behavior: if it exists, the existing file
is removed with all its hashes

Signed-off-by: Alexandre Bruyelles <git@jack.fr.eu.org>

commit.message:
file_scan: do not invalidate a file renamed since the last run

Path are stored in the hashfile because we need to open(2) it for
deduplication.
However, during the scan file, path is not really used: we identify
the files based on their inode number (and subvolume id for btrfs).

Between runs, a file may be renamed: in this case, its ino won't change,
nor its content, so the scan phase used to do nothing.
Yet later, the dedupe would try to open the old path, fails and
conclude that the file were removed.

This patch improve the scan phase to detect the rename and update
the hashfile accordingly.

Signed-off-by: Alexandre Bruyelles <git@jack.fr.eu.org>

commit.message:
util.c: make debug helper `-Wformat-security`-clean

Without the change `gcc-14` fails the build with `-Werror=format-security`
as:

    util.c:340:25: error: format not a string literal and no format arguments [-Werror=format-security]
      340 |         fprintf(stream, buf);
          |                         ^~~

It's a harmless warning as `UUID` has a well-defined set of characters.
But `fputs()` expresses intent more directly to print the string as is.
